# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bitcoin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The **bitcoin protocol** is the set of rules that govern the functioning of bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Its key components and principles are: a peer-to-peer decentralized network with no central oversight; the blockchain technology, a public ledger that records all bitcoin transactions; mining and proof of work, the process to create new bitcoins and verify transactions; and cryptographic security.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Users broadcast cryptographically signed messages to the network using bitcoin cryptocurrency wallet software.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] These messages are proposed transactions, changes to be made in the ledger.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Each node has a copy of the ledger's entire transaction history.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If a transaction violates the rules of the bitcoin protocol, it is ignored, as transactions only occur when the entire network reaches a consensus that they should take place.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This "full network consensus" is achieved when each node on the network verifies the results of a proof-of-work operation called *mining*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Mining packages groups of transactions into blocks, and produces a hash code that follows the rules of the bitcoin protocol.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Creating this hash requires expensive energy, but a network node can verify the hash is valid using very little energy.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If a miner proposes a block to the network, and its hash is valid, the block and its ledger changes are added to the blockchain, and the network moves on to yet unprocessed transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] In case there is a dispute, then the longest chain is considered to be correct.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A new block is created every 10 minutes, on average.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Changes to the bitcoin protocol require consensus among the network participants.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin protocol has inspired the creation of numerous other digital currencies and blockchain-based technologies, making it a foundational technology in the field of cryptocurrencies.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Blockchain technology is a decentralized and secure digital ledger that records transactions across a network of computers.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] It ensures transparency, immutability, and tamper resistance, making data manipulation difficult.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Blockchain is the underlying technology for cryptocurrencies like bitcoin and has applications beyond finance, such as supply chain management and smart contracts.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The network requires minimal structure to share transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] An ad hoc decentralized network of volunteers is sufficient.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Messages are broadcast on a best-effort basis, and nodes can leave and rejoin the network at will.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Upon reconnection, a node downloads and verifies new blocks from other nodes to complete its local copy of the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system or a proof-of-transaction to form a distributed timestamp server as a peer-to-peer network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This work is often called *bitcoin mining*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] During mining, practically all of the computing power of the bitcoin network is used to solve cryptographic tasks, which is proof of work.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Their purpose is to ensure that the generation of valid blocks involves a certain amount of effort so that subsequent modification of the blockchain, such as in the 51% attack scenario, can be practically ruled out.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Because of the difficulty, miners form "mining pools" to get payouts despite these high power requirements, costly hardware deployments, and hardware under control.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As a result of the Chinese ban on bitcoin mining in 2021, the United States currently holds the largest share of bitcoin mining pools.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Requiring a proof of work to accept a new block to the blockchain was Satoshi Nakamoto's key innovation.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The mining process involves identifying a block that, when hashed twice with SHA-256, yields a number smaller than the given difficulty target.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] While the average work required increases in inverse proportion to the difficulty target, a hash can always be verified by executing a single round of double SHA-256.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] For the bitcoin timestamp network, a valid proof of work is found by incrementing a nonce until a value is found that gives the block's hash the required number of leading zero bits.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Once the hashing has produced a valid result, the block cannot be changed without redoing the work.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As later blocks are chained after it, the work to change the block would include redoing the work for each subsequent block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If there is a deviation in consensus then a blockchain fork can occur.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Majority consensus in bitcoin is represented by the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If a majority of computing power is controlled by honest nodes, the honest chain will grow fastest and outpace any competing chains.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] To modify a past block, an attacker would have to redo the proof-of-work of that block and all blocks after it and then surpass the work of the honest nodes.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The probability of a slower attacker catching up diminishes exponentially as subsequent blocks are added.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] To compensate for increasing hardware speed and varying interest in running nodes over time, the difficulty of finding a valid hash is adjusted roughly every two weeks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If blocks are generated too quickly, the difficulty increases and more hashes are required to make a block and to generate new bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The chips pictured have become obsolete due to increasing difficulty.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] to housing and operating large amounts of high-performance mining hardware.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin mining is a competitive endeavor.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin-specific ASICs are now the primary method of mining bitcoin and have surpassed GPU speed by as much as 300-fold.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The difficulty of the mining process is periodically adjusted to the mining power active on the network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As bitcoins have become more difficult to mine, computer hardware manufacturing companies have seen an increase in sales of high-end ASIC products.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Computing power is often bundled together or "pooled" to reduce variance in miner income.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Individual mining rigs often have to wait for long periods to confirm a block of transactions and receive payment.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] In a pool, all participating miners get paid every time a participating server solves a block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This payment depends on the amount of work an individual miner contributed to help find that block, and the payment system used by the pool.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The environmental impact of bitcoin has been characterized in the literature as significant, particularly due to its energy use, greenhouse gas emissions, and electronic waste.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin mining, the process by which bitcoins are created and transactions are finalized, is energy-consuming and results in carbon emissions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] According to the 2025 Cambridge Digital Mining Industry Report, surveyed miners reported that 48% of their electricity came from fossil fuels and 52% from sustainable energy sources, including renewables and nuclear.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Moreover, bitcoins are mined on specialized computer hardware resulting in electronic waste.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As of 2025, several empirical studies report an association between higher bitcoin-mining electricity use and worse environmental-sustainability indicators.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin's environmental impact has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to incentives or restrictions in various jurisdictions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A 2023 study in *ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering* found potential economic benefits from using bitcoin mining at planned renewable-energy installations in the United States.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] By convention, the first transaction in a block is a special transaction that produces new bitcoins owned by the creator of the block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This is the incentive for nodes to support the network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] It provides a way to move new bitcoins into circulation.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The reward for mining halves every 210,000 blocks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] It started at 50 bitcoin, dropped to 25 in late 2012, dropped again to 12.5 on the summer of 2016, and to 6.25 bitcoin in 2020.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The most recent halving, which occurred on 20 April 2024 at 12:09am UTC (with block number 840,000), reduced the block reward to 3.125 bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The next halving is expected to occur in 2028, when the block reward will fall to 1.625 bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This halving process is programmed to continue a maximum of 64 times before new coin creation ceases.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Each miner can choose which transactions are included in or exempted from a block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A greater number of transactions in a block does not equate to greater computational power required to solve that block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As noted in Nakamoto's whitepaper, it is possible to verify bitcoin payments without running a full network node (simplified payment verification, SPV).
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A user only needs a copy of the block headers of the longest chain, which are available by querying network nodes until it is apparent that the longest chain has been obtained; then, get the Merkle tree branch linking the transaction to its block.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Linking the transaction to a place in the chain demonstrates that a network node has accepted it, and blocks added after it further establish the confirmation.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Various potential attacks on the bitcoin network and its use as a payment system, real or theoretical, have been considered.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin protocol includes several features that protect it against some of those attacks, such as unauthorized spending, double spending, forging bitcoins, and tampering with the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Other attacks, such as theft of private keys, require due care by users.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Unauthorized spending is mitigated by bitcoin's implementation of public-private key cryptography.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] For example, when Alice sends a bitcoin to Bob, Bob becomes the new owner of the bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Eve, observing the transaction, might want to spend the bitcoin Bob just received, but she cannot sign the transaction without the knowledge of Bob's private key.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A specific problem that an internet payment system must solve is double-spending, whereby a user pays the same coin to two or more different recipients.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] An example of such a problem would be if Eve sent a bitcoin to Alice and later sent the same bitcoin to Bob.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin network guards against double-spending by recording all bitcoin transfers in a ledger (the blockchain) that is visible to all users, and ensuring for all transferred bitcoins that they have not been previously spent.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If Eve offers to pay Alice a bitcoin in exchange for goods and signs a corresponding transaction, it is still possible that she also creates a different transaction at the same time sending the same bitcoin to Bob.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] By the rules, the network accepts only one of the transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This is called a race attack, since there is a race between the recipients to accept the transaction first.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Alice can reduce the risk of race attack stipulating that she will not deliver the goods until Eve's payment to Alice appears in the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] A variant race attack (which has been called a Finney attack by reference to Hal Finney) requires the participation of a miner.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Instead of sending both payment requests (to pay Bob and Alice with the same coins) to the network, Eve issues only Alice's payment request to the network, while the accomplice tries to mine a block that includes the payment to Bob instead of Alice.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] There is a positive probability that the rogue miner will succeed before the network, in which case the payment to Alice will be rejected.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] As with the plain race attack, Alice can reduce the risk of a Finney attack by waiting for the payment to be included in the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Each block that is added to the blockchain, starting with the block containing a given transaction, is called a confirmation of that transaction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Ideally, merchants and services that receive payment in bitcoin should wait for at least a few confirmations to be distributed over the network before assuming that the payment was done.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The more confirmations that the merchant waits for, the more difficult it is for an attacker to successfully reverse the transaction—unless the attacker controls more than half the total network power, in which case it is called a 51% attack, or a majority attack.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Although more difficult for attackers of a smaller size, there may be financial incentives that make history modification attacks profitable.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The cryptographic primitives employed by Bitcoin are pre-quantum and therefore vulnerable to an attack from a adversary with a cryptographically-relevant, general-purpose quantum computer.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The Bitcoin protocol uses the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) to sign and verify transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] ECDSA is vulnerable to attacks from a quantum computer due to its reliance on the security of the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The Bitcoin protocol allows senders to send Bitcoin to the hash of the recipient's public key.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The hash obscures the public key of the recipient and is therefore quantum-resistant while unspent.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] However, in order for the recipient to transact with the received bitcoin, the recipient would need to broadcast their public key.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] This broadcast could allow a quantum-enabled attacker to derive the private key from the public key and steal the Bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Additionally, the security of the proof of work may be vulnerable to a general-purpose quantum computer with sufficient depth and stability to perform hashing.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Grover's algorithm can be applied to the hash-based proof of work of the Bitcoin protocol to quadratically reduce the time it takes to find a valid nonce.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If such quantum computers were available that could perform Grover's algorithm on a hash-based, proof-of-work blockchain, an attacker would very likely be capable of performing a 51% attack due to the massive speed-up.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin scalability refers to the capability of the Bitcoin network to handle large amounts of transaction data on its platform.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Records (known as *blocks*) in the Bitcoin blockchain are limited in size and frequency to prioritize security and decentralization by keeping the cost of running a Bitcoin node affordable.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] With an average block creation time of 10 minutes and a block size limit of around 1 megabyte, the base layer processes an estimated 3.3 to 7 transactions per second.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Deanonymisation is a strategy in data mining in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other sources of data to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] Along with transaction graph analysis, which may reveal connections between bitcoin addresses (pseudonyms), there is a possible attack which links a user's pseudonym to its IP address.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] If the peer is using Tor, the attack includes a method to separate the peer from the Tor network, forcing them to use their real IP address for any further transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin-protocol] The cost of the attack on the full bitcoin network was estimated to be under €1500 per month, as of 2014.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin works through the collaboration of computers, each of which acts as a node in the peer-to-peer bitcoin network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Each node maintains an independent copy of a public distributed ledger of transactions, called a blockchain, without central oversight.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Transactions are validated through the use of cryptography, preventing one person from spending another person's bitcoin, as long as the owner of the bitcoin keeps certain sensitive data secret.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called mining, which is performed by purpose-built computers.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Mining consumes large quantities of electricity, with surveyed miners reporting that 52% of their electricity use came from sustainable energy sources, and has been criticized for its environmental impact.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Before bitcoin, several digital cash technologies were released, starting with David Chaum's ecash in the 1980s.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The idea that solutions to computational puzzles could have some value was first proposed by cryptographers Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in 1992.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The concept was independently rediscovered by Adam Back who developed Hashcash, a proof-of-work scheme for spam control in 1997.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The first proposals for distributed digital scarcity-based cryptocurrencies came from cypherpunks Wei Dai (b-money) and Nick Szabo (bit gold) in 1998.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2004, Hal Finney developed the first currency based on reusable proof of work.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] These various attempts were not successful: Chaum's concept required centralized control and no banks wanted to sign on, Hashcash had no protection against double-spending, while b-money and bit gold were not resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The domain name *bitcoin.org* was registered on 18 August 2008.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] On 31 October 2008, a link to a white paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled *Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System* was posted to a cryptography mailing list.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to computer scientist Arvind Narayanan, all individual components of bitcoin originated in earlier academic literature.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nakamoto's innovation was their complex interplay which resulted in the first decentralized, Sybil resistant, Byzantine fault tolerant digital cash system, that would eventually be referred to as the first blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nakamoto's paper was not peer-reviewed and was initially ignored by academics, who argued that it could not work.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nakamoto released bitcoin as open-source software.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] On 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network was created when Nakamoto mined the starting block of the chain, known as the *genesis block*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Embedded in this block was the text "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks", which is the date and headline of an issue of *The Times* newspaper.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nine days later, Hal Finney received the first bitcoin transaction: ten bitcoins from Nakamoto.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Wei Dai and Nick Szabo were also early supporters.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] On May 22, 2010, the first known commercial transaction using bitcoin occurred when programmer Laszlo Hanyecz bought two Papa John's pizzas for ₿10,000, in what would later be celebrated as "Bitcoin Pizza Day".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Satoshi tasked Finnish developer and early Bitcoin contributor Martti Malmi with creating content for the bitcoin.org website.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Blockchain analysts estimate that Nakamoto had mined about one million bitcoins before he disappeared in 2010 and handed the network alert key and control of the code repository over to Gavin Andresen.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Andresen later became lead developer at the Bitcoin Foundation, an organization founded in September 2012 to promote bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] After early "proof-of-concept" transactions, the first major users of bitcoin were black markets, such as the dark web Silk Road.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] During its 30 months of existence, beginning in February 2011, Silk Road exclusively accepted bitcoins as payment, transacting ₿9.9 million, worth about $214 million.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In May 2013, US authorities seized the unregistered exchange Mt.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In June 2013, the US Drug Enforcement Administration seized ₿11.02 from an individual attempting to use them to purchase illicit drugs.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This marked the first time a government agency had seized bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The FBI seized about ₿30,000 in October 2013 from Silk Road, following the arrest of its founder Ross Ulbricht.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In December 2013, the People's Bank of China prohibited Chinese financial institutions from using bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] After the announcement, the value of bitcoin dropped, and Baidu no longer accepted bitcoins for certain services.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Buying real-world goods with any virtual currency had been illegal in China since at least 2009.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Research produced by the University of Cambridge estimated that in 2017, there were 2.9 to 5.8 million unique users using a cryptocurrency wallet, most of them using bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In August 2017, the SegWit software upgrade was activated.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Segwit was intended to support the Lightning Network as well as improve scalability.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] SegWit opponents, who supported larger blocks as a scalability solution, forked to create Bitcoin Cash, one of many forks of bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In December 2017, the first futures on bitcoin was introduced by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In February 2018, the price crashed after China imposed a complete ban on bitcoin trading.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The percentage of bitcoin trading in the Chinese renminbi fell from over 90% in September 2017 to less than 1% in June 2018.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] During the same year, bitcoin prices were negatively affected by several hacks or thefts from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2020, some major companies and institutions started to acquire bitcoin: MicroStrategy invested $250 million in bitcoin as a treasury reserve asset, Square, Inc., $50 million, and MassMutual, $100 million.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In November 2020, PayPal added support for bitcoin in the US.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In February 2021, bitcoin's market capitalization reached $1 trillion for the first time.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In November 2021, the Taproot soft-fork upgrade was activated, adding support for Schnorr signatures, improved functionality of smart contracts and Lightning Network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Before, bitcoin only used a custom elliptic curve with the ECDSA algorithm to produce signatures.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In September 2021, bitcoin became legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In October 2021, the first bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund (ETF), called BITO, from ProShares was approved by the SEC and listed on the CME.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In early 2022, during the Canadian trucker protests opposing COVID-19 vaccine mandates, organizers turned to bitcoin to receive donations after traditional financial platforms restricted access to funding.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Proponents highlighted bitcoin's use as a tool for fundraising in situations where access to conventional financial systems may be restricted.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In May and June 2022, the bitcoin price fell following the collapses of TerraUSD, a stablecoin, and the Celsius Network, a cryptocurrency loan company.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2023, ordinals—non-fungible tokens (NFTs)—on bitcoin, went live.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of June 2023, River Financial estimated that bitcoin had 81.7 million users, about 1% of the global population.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In January 2024, the first 11 US spot bitcoin ETFs began trading, offering direct exposure to bitcoin for the first time on American stock exchanges.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In December 2024, bitcoin price reached $100,000 for the first time, as US president-elect Donald Trump promised to make the US the "crypto capital of the planet" and to stockpile bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The same month, BlackRock, the world's largest asset manager, recommended investors to allocate up to 2% of their portfolio to bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2025, the Salvadoran government continues to describe Bitcoin as legal tender under the 2021 Bitcoin Law; however, a January 2025 reform removed obligations for businesses and the government to accept it, so many analysts regard its legal-tender status as effectively ended in practice.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In March 2025, President Trump signed an executive order to establish a strategic bitcoin reserve.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Later that year, some U.S. states, such as Texas and New Hampshire also instituted strategic bitcoin reserves, and the Czech National Bank bought less than €1 million in a "test portfolio".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin logos made by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2009 (left) and 2010 (right).
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The unit of account of the bitcoin system is the *bitcoin*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] It is most commonly represented with the symbol ₿ designed in 2010 and the currency code BTC.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] However, the BTC code does not conform to ISO 4217 as BT is the country code of Bhutan, and ISO 4217 requires the first letter used in global commodities to be 'X'.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] XBT, a code that conforms to ISO 4217 though not officially part of it, is used by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] No uniform capitalization convention exists; some sources use *Bitcoin*, capitalized, to refer to the technology and network, and *bitcoin*, lowercase, for the unit of account.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The *Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary* and the *Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary* use the capitalized and lowercase variants without distinction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] One bitcoin is divisible to eight decimal places.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Units for smaller amounts of bitcoin are the millibitcoin (mBTC), equal to 1⁄1000 bitcoin, and the satoshi (sat), representing 1⁄100000000 (one hundred millionth) bitcoin, the smallest amount possible.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As a decentralized system, bitcoin operates without a central authority or single administrator, so that anyone can create a new bitcoin address and transact without needing any approval.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This is accomplished through a specialized distributed ledger called a *blockchain* that records bitcoin transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The blockchain is implemented as an ordered list of *blocks*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Each block contains a SHA-256 hash of the previous block, chaining them in chronological order.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The blockchain is maintained by a peer-to-peer network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Individual blocks, public addresses, and transactions within blocks are public information, and can be examined using a blockchain explorer.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nodes validate and broadcast transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Each node maintains a copy of the blockchain for ownership verification.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] A new block is created every 10 minutes on average, updating the blockchain across all nodes without central oversight.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This process tracks bitcoin spending, ensuring each bitcoin is spent only once.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Unlike a traditional ledger that tracks physical currency, bitcoins exist digitally as unspent outputs of transactions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In the blockchain, bitcoins are linked to specific strings called addresses.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Most often, an address encodes a hash of a single public key.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Creating such an address involves generating a random private key and then computing the corresponding address.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This process is almost instant, but the reverse (finding the private key for a given address) is nearly impossible.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Publishing such a bitcoin address does not risk its private key, and it is extremely unlikely to accidentally generate a used key with funds.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] To use bitcoins, owners need their private key to digitally sign transactions, which are verified by the network using the public key, keeping the private key secret.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] An address may encode the hash of a bitcoin script that specifies more complex requirements to spend the funds.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] One common example is "multisig", in which multiple distinct private keys must mutually sign any transaction that attempts to spend the funds.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin transactions use a Forth-like scripting language, involving one or more inputs and outputs.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] When sending bitcoins, a user specifies the recipients' addresses and the amount for each output.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This allows sending bitcoins to several recipients in a single transaction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] To prevent double-spending, each input must refer to a previous unspent output in the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Using multiple inputs is similar to using multiple coins in a cash transaction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As in a cash transaction, the sum of inputs can exceed the intended sum of payments.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In such a case, an additional output can return the change back to the payer.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Unallocated input satoshis in the transaction become the transaction fee.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Losing a private key means losing access to the bitcoins, with no other proof of ownership accepted by the protocol.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] For instance, in 2013, a user lost ₿7,500, valued at US$7.5 million, by accidentally discarding a hard drive with the private key.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] It is estimated that around 20% of all bitcoins are lost.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The private key must also be kept secret as its exposure, such as through a data breach, can lead to theft of the associated bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of December 2017, approximately ₿980,000 had been stolen from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Miners don't directly act as nodes, but do communicate with nodes.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The mining process in bitcoin involves maintaining the blockchain through computer processing power.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Miners group and broadcast new transactions into blocks, which are then verified by the network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Each block must contain a proof of work (PoW) to be accepted, involving finding a nonce number that, combined with the block content, produces a hash numerically smaller than the network's *difficulty target*.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This PoW is simple to verify but hard to generate, requiring many attempts.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] PoW forms the basis of bitcoin's consensus mechanism.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The difficulty of generating a block is deterministically adjusted based on the mining power on the network by changing the difficulty target, which is recalibrated every 2,016 blocks (approximately two weeks) to maintain an average time of ten minutes between new blocks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The process requires significant computational power and specialized hardware.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Miners who successfully create a new block with a valid nonce can collect transaction fees from the included transactions and a fixed reward in bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] To claim this reward, a special transaction called a *coinbase* is included in the block, with the miner as the payee.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] All bitcoins in existence have been created through this type of transaction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This reward is halved every 210,000 blocks until ₿21 million have been issued in total, which is expected to occur around the year 2140.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Afterward, miners will only earn from transaction fees.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] These fees are determined by the transaction's size and the amount of data stored, measured in satoshis per byte.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The proof of work system and the chaining of blocks make blockchain modifications very difficult, as altering one block requires changing all subsequent blocks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As more blocks are added, modifying older blocks becomes increasingly challenging.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In case of disagreement, nodes trust the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] To tamper or censor the ledger, one needs to control the majority of the global hashrate.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The high cost required to reach this level of computational power secures the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The environmental impact of bitcoin mining is controversial and has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to restrictions or incentives in various jurisdictions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2025, a non-peer-reviewed study by the Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance (CCAF) estimated that bitcoin mining represented 0.5% of global electricity consumption and 0.08% of world greenhouse gas emissions, comparable to Slovakia's emissions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] About half of the electricity used is generated through fossil fuels.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Moreover, mining hardware's short lifespan results in electronic waste.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In October 2025, the US was the largest mining country with 38% of the global bitcoin mining market share, followed by Russia (16%) and China (14%, despite all cryptocurrency trading and mining being banned there in 2021).
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, with funds linked to addresses, not real-world identities.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] While the owners of these addresses are not directly identified, all transactions are public on the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Patterns of use, like spending coins from multiple inputs, can hint at a common owner.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Public data can sometimes be matched with known address owners.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin exchanges might also need to collect personal data as per legal requirements.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] For enhanced privacy, users can generate a new address for each transaction.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In the bitcoin network, each bitcoin is treated equally, ensuring basic fungibility.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] However, users and applications can choose to differentiate between bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] While wallets and software treat all bitcoins the same, each bitcoin's transaction history is recorded on the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This public record allows for chain analysis, where users can identify and potentially reject bitcoins from controversial sources.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Gox froze accounts containing bitcoins identified as stolen.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin wallets were the first cryptocurrency wallets, enabling users to store the information necessary to transact bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in 2009 by Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin Core is among the best known clients.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist such as Bitcoin Unlimited.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Wallets can be full clients, with a full copy of the blockchain to check the validity of mined blocks, or lightweight clients, just to send and receive transactions without a local copy of the entire blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Third-party internet services, called online wallets or hot wallets, store users' credentials on their servers, making them susceptible of hacks.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Cold storage protects bitcoins from such hacks by keeping private keys offline, either through specialized hardware wallets or paper printouts.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nakamoto limited the block size to one megabyte.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The limited block size and frequency can lead to delayed processing of transactions, increased fees and a bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The Lightning Network, a second-layer routing network, is a potential scaling solution.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Research shows a trend towards centralization in bitcoin as miners join pools for stable income.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] If a single miner or pool controls more than 50% of the hashing power, it would allow them to censor transactions and double-spend coins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2014, mining pool Ghash.io reached 51% mining power, causing safety concerns, but later voluntarily capped its power at 39.99% for the benefit of the whole network.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] A few entities also dominate other parts of the ecosystem such as the client software, online wallets, and simplified payment verification (SPV) clients.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Sociologist Nigel Dodd argues that the essence of the bitcoin ideology is to remove money from social, as well as governmental, control.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] *The Economist* describes bitcoin as "a techno-anarchist project to create an online version of cash, a way for people to transact without the possibility of interference from malicious governments or banks".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] These philosophical ideas initially attracted libertarians and anarchists.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Money serves three purposes: a store of value, a medium of exchange, and a unit of account.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to *The Economist* in 2014, bitcoin functions best as a medium of exchange.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2015, *The Economist* noted that bitcoins had three qualities useful in a currency: they are "hard to earn, limited in supply and easy to verify".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] However, a 2018 assessment by *The Economist* stated that cryptocurrencies met none of these three criteria.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Per some researchers, as of 2015, bitcoin functions more as a payment system than as a currency.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Shiller wrote that bitcoin has potential as a unit of account for measuring the relative value of goods, as with Chile's Unidad de Fomento, but that "Bitcoin in its present form... doesn't really solve any sensible economic problem".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The legal status of bitcoin varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Because of its decentralized nature and its global presence, regulating bitcoin is difficult.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] However, the use of bitcoin can be criminalized, and shutting down exchanges and the peer-to-peer economy in a given country would constitute a de facto ban.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The use of bitcoin by criminals has attracted the attention of financial regulators, legislative bodies, and law enforcement.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Nobel-prize winning economist Joseph Stiglitz says that bitcoin's anonymity encourages money laundering and other crimes.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] This is the main justification behind bitcoin bans.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of November 2021, nine countries applied an absolute ban (Algeria, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, Qatar, and Tunisia) while another 42 countries had an implicit ban.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to Harvard Professor Kenneth Rogoff as of 2025, bitcoin is rarely used in regular transactions with merchants, but is popular in the informal economy and for criminal activities.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Prices are not usually quoted in bitcoin and trades involve conversions into fiat currencies.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Commonly cited reasons for not using bitcoin include high costs, the inability to process chargebacks, high price volatility, long transaction times, and transaction fees (especially for small purchases).
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] *Bloomberg* reported that bitcoin was being used for large-item purchases on the site Overstock.com and for cross-border payments to freelancers.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2015, there was little sign of bitcoin use in international remittances despite high fees charged by banks and Western Union.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] From September 2021 until January 2025, the Bitcoin Law made bitcoin a legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The adoption had been criticized internationally and within El Salvador.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2022, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) urged El Salvador to reverse its decision.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2022, the use of Bitcoin in El Salvador remained low: 80% of businesses refused to accept it.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2025, El Salvador's government revoked bitcoin's status as legal tender currency in order to comply with conditions set by the IMF for a loan.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] El Salvador still describes bitcoin as "legal tender", but its acceptance is no longer obligitory (as it is with the US dollar) and the El Salvador government no longer accepts bitcoin for payment of taxes or fees.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In April 2022, the Central African Republic (CAR) adopted bitcoin as legal tender alongside the CFA franc, but repealed the reform one year later.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin is also used by some governments.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] For instance, the Iranian government initially opposed cryptocurrencies, but later began using them to circumvent sanctions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Since 2020, Iran has required local bitcoin miners to sell bitcoin to the Central Bank of Iran, allowing the central bank to use it for imports.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Some constituent states and local governments also accept tax payments in bitcoin, including Colorado in the US and Zug and Lugano in Switzerland.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2023, the US government owned more than $5 billion worth of seized bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of 2018, the overwhelming majority of bitcoin transactions took place on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Since 2014, regulated bitcoin funds also allow exposure to the asset or to futures as an investment.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin is used as a store of value: individuals and companies such as the Winklevoss twins and Elon Musk's companies SpaceX and Tesla have each bought and sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of bitcoin.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin wealth is highly concentrated, with 0.01% holding 27% of in-circulation currency, as of 2021.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] As of March 2025, El Salvador had $550 million worth of bitcoin in its international reserves, about 6,102 coins.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin, along with other cryptocurrencies, has been described as an economic bubble by several economists, including Nobel Prize in Economics laureates, such as Joseph Stiglitz, James Heckman, and Paul Krugman.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Another recipient of the prize, Robert Shiller, argues that bitcoin is rather a fad that may become an asset class.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] He describes its price growth as an "epidemic", driven by contagious narratives.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2024, Jean Tirole, also Nobel laureate, described bitcoin as a "pure bubble" as its intrinsic value is zero.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to him, some bubbles are long-lasting such as gold and fiat currencies, and it is impossible to predict whether bitcoin would implode like other financial bubbles or become an alternative to gold.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The same year, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell described bitcoin as a digital competitor to gold but not to the dollar as he argued it is a highly volatile speculative asset not used as a form of payment.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2025, Kenneth Rogoff claimed that Krugman was wrong and that Bitcoin had value as it is competing with the dollar to become the means of exchange of the underground economy which represents 20% of the world's GDP.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to Rogoff, bitcoin is "the ideal currency for a more fragmented and uncertain global landscape" and it could become appealing to emerging-market central banks as a "politically neutral" reserve currency.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to research published in the *International Review of Financial Analysis* in 2018, bitcoin as an asset is highly volatile and does not behave like any other conventional asset.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] According to one 2022 analysis published in *The Journal of Alternative Investments*, bitcoin was less volatile than oil, silver, US Treasuries, and 190 stocks in the S&P 500 during and after the 2020 stock market crash.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The term *hodl* was created in December 2013 for holding bitcoin rather than selling it during periods of volatility.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] In 2014, economist Nouriel Roubini described bitcoin as a Ponzi scheme.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Legal scholar Eric Posner disagrees, however, as "a real Ponzi scheme takes fraud; bitcoin, by contrast, seems more like a collective delusion".
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] A 2014 World Bank report also concluded that bitcoin was not a deliberate Ponzi scheme.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin markets operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, contrasting with traditional financial markets that have fixed trading hours.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] Bitcoin prices show much higher volatility and respond strongly to both regulatory changes and market events.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The volume of bitcoin trading can fluctuate considerably among various exchanges and geographic regions.
[src:bitcoin/bitcoin] The daily transaction volume of bitcoin across all exchanges typically reaches $50 billion as of 2025.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Forks are related to the fact that different parties need to use common rules to maintain the history of the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] When parties are not in agreement, alternative chains may emerge.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] While most forks are short-lived some are permanent.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Short-lived forks are due to the difficulty of reaching fast consensus in a distributed system.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Blockchain forks have been widely discussed in the context of the bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Forks can be classified as *accidental* or *intentional*.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] *Accidental fork* happens when two or more miners find a block at nearly the same time.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The fork is resolved when subsequent block(s) are added and one of the chains becomes longer than the alternative(s).
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The network abandons the blocks that are not in the longest chain (they are called *orphaned* blocks).
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] A *source code fork* or *project fork* is when developers take a copy of source code from one cryptocurrency project and start **independent** development on it, creating a separate and new piece of blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Such examples are; Litecoin a source code fork of Bitcoin, Monero fork of Bytecoin and Dogecoin fork of Litecoin.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] A *soft fork* is a backward-compatible change to the blockchain protocol that allows new rules to be introduced without requiring all users to upgrade their software.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] In a soft fork, a majority of the network’s miners implement the new rules and begin following the updated version of the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The rest of the network can continue to follow the blockchain, but they will be unable to validate that new blocks follow the updated rules.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Because a soft fork is backward-compatible, it does not result in the creation of a new blockchain or the splitting of the network.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Instead, it allows the network to gradually transition to the new rules while still maintaining compatibility with the old rules.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] A *permanent chain split* is described as a case when there are two or more permanent versions of a blockchain sharing the same history up to a certain time, after which the histories start to differ.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Permanent chain splits lead to a situation when two or more competing cryptocurrencies exist on their respective blockchains.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The taxation of cryptocurrency splits varies substantially from state to state.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The ATO does not classify cryptocurrency splits as taxation events.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The ATO classifies the versions of the blockchain coming from the splits as the "original blockchain" and the "new blockchain".
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] In relation to the cost base, the cryptocurrency on the original blockchain should be assigned all the original cost base, while the cryptocurrency on the new blockchain should be assigned cost base zero.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The UK HMRC does not classify cryptocurrency splits as taxation events.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] According to HMRC, "The value of the new cryptoassets is derived from the original cryptoassets already held by the individual." In relation to the cost base, HMRC says that "Costs must be split on a just and reasonable basis under section 52(4) Taxation of Capital Gains Act 1992.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] HMRC does not prescribe any particular apportionment method.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] As of September 2021, it is believed that more than 2.3 million people in the UK own a cryptoasset.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] As these assets do not physically exist, HMRC has been forced to issue guidance stating that cryptoassets will follow the residence of the beneficial owner.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] Residents in the UK who trade cryptoassets, no matter where these assets are "held", will be liable to UK taxes.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] However, there is a growing belief that this guidance may well be challenged in the courts.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] The US Internal Revenue Service (IRS) classifies cryptocurrency splits as "airdrops" and as taxable events.
[src:bitcoin/fork-blockchain] According to the guidance published by IRS, provided the taxpayer is in possession of the keys, they are obliged to pay tax for the new cryptocurrency using the fair market value of the cryptocurrency as their income.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The **Lightning Network** (**LN**) is a payment protocol built on the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] It is intended to enable fast transactions among participating nodes (independently run members of the network) and has been proposed as a solution to the bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Joseph Poon and Thaddeus Dryja published a Lightning Network white paper in February 2015.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Lightning Labs launched the Lightning Network in 2018 with the goal of reducing the cost and time required for cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Specifically, the bitcoin blockchain can only process around 7 transactions per second (compared to Visa Inc., which can process around 24,000 transactions per second).
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Despite initial enthusiasm for the Lightning Network, reports on social media of failed transactions, security vulnerabilities, and over-complication led to a decline in interest.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The three major Lightning Network implementations are Lightning Network Daemon (LND) by Lightning Labs, Core Lightning (CLN) by Blockstream, and Eclair by ACINQ.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] A fourth implementation library, Lightning Development Kit (LDK), is maintained by Spiral, a subsidiary of Block, Inc.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] On January 19, 2019, pseudonymous Twitter user hodlonaut began a game-like promotional test of the Lightning Network by sending 100,000 satoshis (0.001 bitcoin) to a trusted recipient where each recipient added 10,000 satoshis ($0.34 at the time) to send to the next trusted recipient.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The "lightning torch" payment reached notable personalities including former Twitter A.K.A X CEO Jack Dorsey, Litecoin Creator Charlie Lee, Lightning Labs CEO Elizabeth Stark, and Binance CEO "CZ" Changpeng Zhao, among others.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Andreas Antonopoulos calls the Lightning Network a second layer routing network.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The payment channels allow participants to transfer money to each other without having to make all their transactions public on the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] This is secured by penalizing uncooperative participants.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] When opening a channel, participants must commit an amount on the blockchain (a *funding transaction*).
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Time-based script extensions like `CheckSequenceVerify` and `CheckLockTimeVerify` make the penalties possible.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Transacting parties use the Lightning Network by opening a payment channel and transferring (committing) funds to the relevant layer-1 blockchain (e.g. bitcoin) under a smart contract.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The parties then make any number of off-chain Lightning Network transactions that update the tentative distribution of the channel's funds, without broadcasting to the blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Whenever the parties have finished their transaction session, they close the payment channel, and the smart contract distributes the committed funds according to the transaction record.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The Lightning Network (LN) operates through bidirectional payment channels between two nodes, forming smart contracts that facilitate off-chain transactions.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] If either party closes a channel, the final state is settled on the Bitcoin blockchain.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] While this design enables faster and cheaper transactions, the necessity of on-chain transactions to open and close channels introduces scalability constraints.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] To preserve privacy and security, the network employs an **onion routing** protocol, wherein each node in the path decrypts only enough information to determine the next hop, without knowledge of the payment's origin or final destination.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] As of March 2026, the Lightning Network had over 17,000 public nodes and approximately 40,000 public payment channels, with a total network capacity of around 4,900 BTC.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Bitcoin was originally intended to be a peer-to-peer electronic cash system.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] A notable early example occurred in May 2010 when Laszlo Hanyecz paid 10,000 BTC for two pizzas—an event now noted annually as *Bitcoin Pizza Day*.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] As Bitcoin's value and network congestion increased, this use was no longer practical.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] The Lightning Network is intended to address this and to make peer-to-peer payments more practical.
[src:bitcoin/lightning-network] Several cryptocurrency wallets offer support for the Lightning Network, including Phoenix, Cash App, Muun, Zeus, and Breez.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] The Litecoin blockchain is similar to the bitcoin codebase, modified for lower transaction fees.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] By 2011, bitcoin mining was largely performed by GPUs.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] This raised concern in some users that mining now had a high barrier to entry, and that CPU resources were becoming obsolete and worthless for mining.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] Using code from bitcoin, a new alternative currency was created called *Tenebrix* (TBX).
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] Tenebrix replaced the SHA-256 rounds in bitcoin's mining algorithm with the *scrypt* function, which had been specifically designed in 2009 to be expensive to accelerate with FPGA or ASIC chips.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] This would allow Tenebrix to have been "GPU-resistant", and utilize the available CPU resources from bitcoin miners.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] Tenebrix itself was a successor project to an earlier cryptocurrency which replaced bitcoin's issuance schedule with a constant block reward (thus creating an unlimited money supply).
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] However, the developers included a clause in the code that would allow them to claim 7.7 million TBX for themselves at no cost, which was criticized by users.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] To address this, Charlie Lee, a Google employee who would later become engineering director at Coinbase, created an alternative version of Tenebrix called *Fairbrix* (FBX).
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] Lee released Litecoin via an open-source client on GitHub on October 7, 2011.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] After launch, the early growth of Litecoin was aided by its increasing exchange availability and liquidity on early exchanges such as BTC-e.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] During the month of November 2013, the aggregate value of Litecoin experienced massive growth which included a 100% leap within 24 hours.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] In early 2014, Lee suggested merge mining (auxPOW) Dogecoin with Litecoin to the Dogecoin community at large.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] In September 2014, Dogecoin began merge-mining with Litecoin.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] In 2020, PayPal added the ability for users to purchase a derivative of Litecoin along with bitcoin, Ethereum, and Bitcoin Cash which could not be withdrawn or spent as part of its Crypto feature.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] In September 2021, a fake press release was published on GlobeNewswire announcing a partnership between Litecoin and Walmart.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] This caused the price of Litecoin to increase by around 30%, before the press release was revealed as a hoax.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] In May 2022, MWEB (Mimblewimble Extension Blocks) upgrade was activated on the Litecoin network as a soft fork.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] This upgrade provides users with the option of sending confidential Litecoin transactions, in which the amount being sent is only known between the sender and receiver.
[src:bitcoin/litecoin] Third-party vendors providing point of sale infrastructure for Litecoin include BitPay.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] SegWit had Bitcoin Improvement Proposal number BIP 141.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The declared purpose was to prevent nonintentional bitcoin transaction malleability; allow optional data transmission; and to bypass certain protocol restrictions (such as the block size limit) with a soft fork.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Segregated Witness was activated on 24 August 2017.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] It was also intended to mitigate a blockchain size limitation problem that reduces Bitcoin transaction speed.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] It does this by splitting the transaction into two segments, removing the unlocking signature ("witness" data) from the original portion and appending it as a separate structure at the end.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The original section would continue to hold the sender and receiver data, and the new "witness" structure would contain scripts and signatures.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The original data segment would be counted normally, but the "witness" segment would, in effect, be counted as a quarter of its real size.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Bitcoin is a cryptocurrency, a form of currency using cryptography to keep transactions secure.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] A collection of bitcoin transactions prefaced by a block header, protected by proof of work, and recorded on a network of computers is called a "block".
[src:bitcoin/segwit] All blocks are tied together sequentially by using a cryptographic hash on the previous block and storing its output in the next.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Each block contains information about who sends and receives a given unit of bitcoin (a transaction), as well as the signature(s) that approve each transaction.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Originally, there was no limit to the size of blocks.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] However, this allowed malicious actors to make up fake "block" data that was very long as a form of denial-of-service attack (DoS attack).
[src:bitcoin/segwit] These fake blocks would be detected, but doing so would take a very long time, slowing down the whole system.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Therefore, a block size limit of 1 MB was introduced.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The current Bitcoin blockchain design is regarded as having two shortcomings: scalability and malleability.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] A new block is added to the chain at random intervals, averaging, by design, ten minutes (proof of work causes this delay).
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Together with the limit on block-size, this limits the number of transactions that can be processed in a given time.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Some sites work around this problem by using "off-chain payments" conducting transactions without writing them to the blockchain which involves various trade-offs regarding trust and transaction finality.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Others have proposed changes to Bitcoin that would reform the block format in a backward-incompatible way.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] For example, FlexTrans (Flexible Transactions) would make transactions smaller by changing how they are described to a "tag" system, allowing more transactions per block.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] This is not compatible with systems that do not upgrade.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] A transaction uses unused outputs from a previous transaction(s) known as unspent transaction outputs (UTXO).
[src:bitcoin/segwit] This results in a chain of related transactions linked by their transaction identifier.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] However, it is possible for someone to change (mutate) unconfirmed bitcoin transactions without making them invalid, which changes the transaction's identifier, making child transactions invalid (i.e., link between transactions are broken).
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The signature data called the *witness* would be separated from the Merkle tree record of who is sending or receiving the bitcoins.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The witness data is moved to the end, and each byte of it would only count as one quarter of a "unit".
[src:bitcoin/segwit] It also addresses signature malleability, by serializing signatures separately from the rest of the transaction data, so that the transaction ID is no longer malleable.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The activation window for the SegWit upgrade started at 00:00 UTC, 15 November 2016, and would run until 00:00 UTC, 15 November 2017.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] SegWit would only be activated once at least 95% of miners signaled readiness for the upgrade across a target adjustment period of 2016 blocks.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] On 9 August 2017, a milestone was reached when 100% of miners between blocks 477,792 to 479,807 signaled support for SegWit, which meant the SegWit upgrade was "locked in" and would be fully activated roughly two weeks later at the start of the following target adjustment period.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] SegWit was then activated on 24 August 2017 at block height 481,824.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] The bitcoin price rose almost 50% in the week following SegWit's activation.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Initially, most bitcoin transactions have not been able to use the upgrade.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] In the first week of October, the proportion of network transactions using SegWit rose from 7% to 10%, indicating an increase in use rate.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] A small group of mostly China-based bitcoin miners, that were unhappy with bitcoin's proposed SegWit improvement plans, pushed forward alternative plans for a split which created Bitcoin Cash.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] As of February 2018, SegWit transactions exceed 30%.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] Segregated Witness (BIP 141) should not be confused with SegWit2x (SegWit2Mb).
[src:bitcoin/segwit] As of mid-2017, the SegWit2x proposal had support from over 90% of the hash rate.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] However, the proposal has been controversial due to the limitation of project work to an invitation-only group of developers.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] In mid-July 2017, it became evident that miners favored implementing the Segwit part of the agreement before 1 August 2017 UASF, aiming to mitigate the risk of a hard fork in the bitcoin network.
[src:bitcoin/segwit] On 8 November 2017, the developers of SegWit2x announced that the hard fork planned for around 16 November 2017 was canceled due to a lack of consensus.
